(275,299,'blogs','18','{\"id\":18,\"status\":\"published\",\"sort\":null,\"user_created\":\"8bf1a523-5059-4ece-8f55-cc361500b3d0\",\"date_created\":\"2024-10-11T11:51:03.000Z\",\"user_updated\":\"8bf1a523-5059-4ece-8f55-cc361500b3d0\",\"date_updated\":\"2024-10-14T04:42:45.000Z\",\"content\":\"<h3><strong>What to Do in Case of a Car Breakdown in Cambodia</strong></h3>\\n<p>Car breakdowns can happen anywhere, but knowing what to do in case of a breakdown in Cambodia can help you stay safe and get back on the road quickly. Here are the steps to take if your rental car breaks down:</p>\\n<h4><strong>1. Move to a Safe Area</strong></h4>\\n<p>If possible, pull over to the side of the road or move to a safe area. Turn on your hazard lights to alert other drivers.</p>\\n<h4><strong>2. Contact the Rental Company</strong></h4>\\n<p>Most rental companies provide roadside assistance. Call the rental company&rsquo;s emergency number to report the issue and get help. Be prepared to provide your location and a description of the problem.</p>\\n<h4><strong>3. Stay with the Vehicle</strong></h4>\\n<p>If you\'re in a remote area, it\'s safer to stay with the vehicle until help arrives. Avoid walking on highways or unfamiliar roads, especially at night.</p>\\n<h4><strong>4. Have a Basic Emergency Kit</strong></h4>\\n<p>Before heading out, check that your rental car has an emergency kit, including a spare tire, flashlight, and first-aid supplies. This can help you handle minor issues while waiting for assistance.</p>\\n<p>By staying calm and following these steps, you can manage a car breakdown safely and efficiently.</p>\",\"thumbnail\":\"bdf3617a-f6e9-449c-9f3e-0d2158822818\",\"title\":\"What to Do in Case of a Car Breakdown in Cambodia\",\"description\":\"Step-by-step instructions on how to handle a car breakdown in Cambodia, including safety tips, contacting your rental company, and roadside assistance.\"}','{\"thumbnail\":\"bdf3617a-f6e9-449c-9f3e-0d2158822818\",\"title\":\"What to Do in Case of a Car Breakdown in Cambodia\",\"description\":\"Step-by-step instructions on how to handle a car breakdown in Cambodia, including safety tips, contacting your rental company, and roadside assistance.\",\"user_updated\":\"8bf1a523-5059-4ece-8f55-cc361500b3d0\",\"date_updated\":\"2024-10-14T04:42:45.521Z\"}',NULL,NULL),
(276,300,'blogs','1','{\"id\":1,\"status\":\"published\",\"sort\":null,\"user_created\":\"8bf1a523-5059-4ece-8f55-cc361500b3d0\",\"date_created\":\"2024-10-11T11:42:20.000Z\",\"user_updated\":\"8bf1a523-5059-4ece-8f55-cc361500b3d0\",\"date_updated\":\"2024-10-14T11:08:09.000Z\",\"content\":\"<h3><strong>Tips for Renting a Car for the First Time (Full Version)</strong></h3>\\n<p>Renting a car for the first time can be both exciting and a little intimidating. Whether you&rsquo;re planning a road trip, need a rental for business, or just want the freedom to explore a new place, having a set of wheels at your disposal is convenient. However, there are a few things to keep in mind to ensure a smooth and stress-free rental experience. Here&rsquo;s a comprehensive guide with practical tips for first-time car renters:</p>\\n<hr>\\n<h4><strong>1. Know What You Need</strong></h4>\\n<p>Before you start searching for a rental, it&rsquo;s important to know what type of vehicle best suits your needs:</p>\\n<ul>\\n<li><strong>Compact Car</strong>: Ideal for city driving, fuel-efficient, and easy to park.</li>\\n<li><strong>SUV or Minivan</strong>: Perfect for road trips or traveling with family and friends, offering extra space for passengers and luggage.</li>\\n<li><strong>Luxury Car</strong>: Great for special occasions or if you simply want to ride in style.</li>\\n<li><strong>Off-Road Vehicle</strong>: Necessary for exploring rugged terrain or going on adventurous trips.</li>\\n</ul>\\n<p>Think about the purpose of your rental, the number of people traveling, and how much luggage or equipment you&rsquo;ll have. Also, consider fuel efficiency if you plan on covering long distances.</p>\\n<hr>\\n<h4><strong>2. Compare Prices Across Multiple Platforms</strong></h4>\\n<p>It&rsquo;s always tempting to go with the first option you find, but doing a bit of research can save you money in the long run. Here are some tips for finding the best deal:</p>\\n<ul>\\n<li><strong>Use Comparison Websites</strong>: Check online platforms like Kayak, Rentalcars.com, or Expedia to compare prices from different car rental companies.</li>\\n<li><strong>Check the Rental Company&rsquo;s Website</strong>: Sometimes, booking directly through the car rental company\'s website offers special promotions or loyalty discounts.</li>\\n<li><strong>Look for Discounts</strong>: Some credit cards, loyalty programs, or memberships (like AAA) may provide discounts on car rentals.</li>\\n<li><strong>Be Aware of Hidden Fees</strong>: These can include additional driver fees, charges for young drivers, late returns, fuel policies, or even airport surcharges. Make sure to read the fine print.</li>\\n</ul>\\n<hr>\\n<h4><strong>3. Understand Car Rental Insurance</strong></h4>\\n<p>Insurance is one of the trickiest aspects of renting a car for the first time. Rental companies will offer you various insurance options, which may include:</p>\\n<ul>\\n<li><strong>Collision Damage Waiver (CDW)</strong>: This protects you from financial responsibility if the rental car is damaged in an accident or stolen.</li>\\n<li><strong>Liability Insurance</strong>: Covers damage or injury you cause to others while driving the rental.</li>\\n<li><strong>Personal Accident Insurance</strong>: Provides medical coverage for you and your passengers in case of an accident.</li>\\n</ul>\\n<p>However, you might already be covered:</p>\\n<ul>\\n<li><strong>Your Personal Car Insurance</strong>: Check your existing car insurance policy. If it includes rental cars, you may not need to purchase additional coverage.</li>\\n<li><strong>Credit Card Coverage</strong>: Many credit cards offer rental car insurance if you pay for the rental using the card. Contact your credit card company to find out what&rsquo;s included.</li>\\n</ul>\\n<p>Avoid double-paying for insurance if you already have adequate coverage. But if you&rsquo;re not covered, consider buying the rental company&rsquo;s insurance for peace of mind.</p>\\n<hr>\\n<h4><strong>4. Book in Advance</strong></h4>\\n<p>Just like flights and hotels, booking your rental car in advance can help you secure a better deal. Prices tend to go up closer to your travel dates, especially during busy seasons. Try to book at least two weeks ahead, if possible.</p>\\n<p>Also, if you\'re planning to rent a car in high-demand areas or during holidays, booking early ensures availability. Last-minute rentals may leave you with limited vehicle choices or higher prices.</p>\\n<hr>\\n<h4><strong>5. Choose the Right Pickup and Drop-off Location</strong></h4>\\n<p>Car rentals at airports are convenient, but they usually come with added fees due to airport surcharges. If you&rsquo;re trying to save money, look for rental locations outside the airport.</p>\\n<p>Additionally, some companies charge extra for dropping off the car at a different location than where you picked it up. If possible, return the vehicle to the same location to avoid this fee, unless your travel plans require a one-way rental.</p>\\n<hr>\\n<h4><strong>6. Inspect the Vehicle Thoroughly</strong></h4>\\n<p>Before you drive off, it&rsquo;s essential to carefully inspect the vehicle for any existing damage. Take the following steps:</p>\\n<ul>\\n<li><strong>Walk Around the Car</strong>: Check for dents, scratches, chipped paint, or cracks in the windows.</li>\\n<li><strong>Inside the Car</strong>: Look for stains, damage to the upholstery, or issues with electronics.</li>\\n<li><strong>Take Photos or Videos</strong>: Document any damages you notice. This provides proof in case the rental company tries to charge you for damage that was already there.</li>\\n<li><strong>Check the Tires and Fuel</strong>: Make sure the tires are properly inflated and the fuel level matches what&rsquo;s indicated in the rental agreement.</li>\\n</ul>\\n<p>Report any damage to the rental company before you leave, and make sure it&rsquo;s noted on your rental agreement to avoid being charged later.</p>\\n<hr>\\n<h4><strong>7. Understand the Fuel Policy</strong></h4>\\n<p>Rental companies have different fuel policies, so make sure you&rsquo;re clear on what&rsquo;s expected:</p>\\n<ul>\\n<li><strong>Full-to-Full</strong>: You&rsquo;ll get the car with a full tank and must return it with a full tank. This is usually the most cost-effective option as you can refuel at local stations.</li>\\n<li><strong>Prepaid Fuel</strong>: You pay in advance for a full tank of fuel and can return the car empty. This option is convenient, but you won&rsquo;t be refunded for any unused fuel.</li>\\n<li><strong>Full-to-Empty</strong>: You may be charged for a full tank of fuel upfront, but rental companies often charge higher-than-average rates for this. Try to avoid this policy if possible.</li>\\n</ul>\\n<p>Returning the car without refueling, if required, can lead to high refueling charges, so be sure to stick to the agreed policy.</p>\\n<hr>\\n<h4><strong>8. Know Your Rental Company&rsquo;s Terms</strong></h4>\\n<p>Every car rental company has different policies, so make sure to read the terms and conditions carefully. Pay attention to:</p>\\n<ul>\\n<li><strong>Mileage Limits</strong>: Some rentals come with unlimited mileage, while others charge for every mile/kilometer over the limit.</li>\\n<li><strong>Driver Requirements</strong>: Most rental companies require drivers to be at least 25 years old, though some will allow younger drivers for an additional fee. You&rsquo;ll also need a valid driver&rsquo;s license.</li>\\n<li><strong>Deposit and Payment</strong>: Check how much deposit is required and how it will be refunded. Ensure that your credit card has enough credit available for the deposit amount.</li>\\n</ul>\\n<hr>\\n<h4><strong>9. Return the Car on Time</strong></h4>\\n<p>Returning the car late, even by an hour, can result in extra fees. Plan your drop-off time carefully and allow for unexpected delays. If you know you&rsquo;ll be late, contact the rental company to see if they offer a grace period.</p>\\n<p>Before you return the car, ensure that:</p>\\n<ul>\\n<li><strong>The Car is Clean</strong>: Remove any trash or personal items. Some companies may charge a cleaning fee if the vehicle is excessively dirty.</li>\\n<li><strong>You&rsquo;ve Followed the Fuel Policy</strong>: If required, refill the tank before returning the car to avoid steep refueling charges.</li>\\n</ul>\\n<hr>\\n<p>Renting a car for the first time can feel overwhelming, but with a little preparation, you can avoid common pitfalls and enjoy a hassle-free experience. By following these tips, you&rsquo;ll be better equipped to find the right vehicle, navigate insurance options, and avoid unexpected fees. Now, you&rsquo;re ready to hit the road with confidence!</p>\",\"thumbnail\":\"d098040f-b633-45b0-b969-b043e98ea67d\",\"title\":\"Tips for Renting a Car for the First Time\",\"description\":\"If it\'s your first time renting a car, here’s a simple guide on everything you need to know: from understanding rental policies to choosing the right insurance and avoiding hidden fees.\"}','{\"content\":\"<h3><strong>Tips for Renting a Car for the First Time (Full Version)</strong></h3>\\n<p>Renting a car for the first time can be both exciting and a little intimidating. Whether you&rsquo;re planning a road trip, need a rental for business, or just want the freedom to explore a new place, having a set of wheels at your disposal is convenient. However, there are a few things to keep in mind to ensure a smooth and stress-free rental experience. Here&rsquo;s a comprehensive guide with practical tips for first-time car renters:</p>\\n<hr>\\n<h4><strong>1. Know What You Need</strong></h4>\\n<p>Before you start searching for a rental, it&rsquo;s important to know what type of vehicle best suits your needs:</p>\\n<ul>\\n<li><strong>Compact Car</strong>: Ideal for city driving, fuel-efficient, and easy to park.</li>\\n<li><strong>SUV or Minivan</strong>: Perfect for road trips o